12 injured employee or reimbursement to an insurer; or (2) concealing, falsifying or
13 failing to provide certain evidence or documents before certain hearings which
14 would have been useful to an injured employee in seeking benefits or
15 compensation.
16 Existing law requires an insurer to keep a list of physicians and chiropractic
17 physicians from which an injured employee may choose to receive treatment from a
18 panel established and maintained by the Administrator. Existing law also sets forth
19 procedures and limitations governing the removal of a physician or chiropractic
20 physician from an insurer’s list. (NRS 616C.087, 616C.090) Section 14 of this bill:
21 (1) prohibits an insurer from removing a physician or chiropractic physician from
22 the insurer’s list except as expressly provided in existing law; and (2) requires an
23 insurer to replace any physician or chiropractic physician who is removed from the
24 list within 60 days. Sections 4, 6, 7, 12 and 13 of this bill: (1) require an insurer to
25 keep a list of certain providers of health care other than a physician or chiropractic
26 physician, which section 1 of this bill designates as an “industrial provider of
27 health care,” from which an injured employee may choose to receive treatment
28 from a panel established and maintained by the Administrator; and (2) establish
29 certain requirements and restrictions concerning the selection of such an industrial
30 provider of health care. Section 2 of this bill makes a conforming change so that
31 the definition of “industrial provider of health care” applies to the provisions of
32 existing law governing industrial insurance.
33 Section 8 of this bill authorizes a hearing officer or appeals officer of the
34 Hearings Division of the Department of Administration to order any needed
35 examination, assessment or treatment of an injured employee be conducted by any
36 physician, chiropractic physician or industrial provider of health care who will
37 accept the fee schedule adopted by the Administrator, whether located in this State
38 or another state, if the hearing or appeals officer finds that there is a lack of
39 physicians, chiropractic physicians or providers available. Section 9 of this bill
40 establishes certain requirements for the filing and service of certain evidence and
41 documents in advance of a hearing before a hearing officer or appeals officer.
42 Existing law requires a treating physician, chiropractic physician, physician
43 assistant or advanced practice registered nurse to complete and file a claim for
44 compensation within 3 working days after first providing treatment for an injured
45 employee, or delegate the duty to do so to a physician assistant or advanced
46 practice registered nurse at a medical facility. (NRS 616C.040, 616C.045) Sections
47 10 and 11 of this bill similarly authorize a treating physician, chiropractic
48 physician, physician assistant or advanced practice registered nurse to delegate the
49 duty to complete and file the claim for compensation to an industrial provider of
50 health care.
51 Existing law provides that an injury or disease sustained by an employee that is
52 caused by stress is compensable under industrial insurance if it arose out of and in
53 the course of his or her employment. Existing law sets forth the manner by which
54 such an injury must be proven to have arisen out of and in the course of the
55 employment. Under existing law, with certain exceptions, such an injury is deemed
56 to arise out of and in the course of employment only if the employee proves certain
57 elements by clear and convincing medical or psychiatric evidence. (NRS 616C.180)
58 Section 17 of this bill eliminates provisions that make such method of proof the
59 only method, with certain exceptions, by which an employee may prove that such
60 an injury arose in and out of the course of employment. Section 17 additionally
61 eliminates the standard of clear and convincing evidence and instead requires proof
62 by medical, psychological or psychiatric evidence.
63 Section 20 of this bill requires the Chief of the Hearings Division of the
64 Department of Administration to maintain and make accessible to the public on the
65 Internet website of the Division, a calendar of all matters which are before hearing
66 officers and appeals officers.
